            <div type="apparatus" resp="#martaf">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text based on photograph</note></app>
                    <app><note>Apparently there is no text before l. 1</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 1"><note>Korhonen: [---&#948;]&#974;&#961;&#945; (possibly &#7992;&#963;&#953;&#948;&#974;&#961;&#945; or &#920;&#949;&#959;&#948;&#974;&#961;&#945;)</note></app>
                    <app loc="lines 1-2"><note>Korhonen: &#963;&#949;&#956;|[&#957;&#959;&#964;&#940;&#964;&#951;]</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 2"><note>Korhonen: [&#956;]&#940;&#956;&#956;&#951; (or &#7936;&#956;&#956;&#942;)</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#martaf">
                <p>&#8230; -dora, the noblest &#8230; mother.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>&#8230; -dora, la nobilissima &#8230; madre.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#martaf">
                <p>The inscription is very fragmentary. Korhonen recognised at ll. 1-2 a traditional epithet characterising women in Christian epitaphs, <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#963;&#949;&#956;&#957;&#959;&#964;&#940;&#964;&#951;</foreign> (other epithets are <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#7936;&#947;&#957;&#959;&#964;&#940;&#964;&#951;</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#960;&#953;&#963;&#964;&#959;&#964;&#940;&#964;&#951;</foreign>, or <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#949;&#8016;&#955;&#945;&#946;&#949;&#963;&#964;&#940;&#964;&#951;</foreign>, on which see F. Grossi Gondi, "Trattato di epigrafia cristiana latina e greca del mondo romano occidentale" (Roma, 1920), 171-177; Korhonen 2004: 111). The name of the deceased was supposed to be either <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#7992;&#963;&#953;&#948;&#974;&#961;&#945;</foreign> or <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#920;&#949;&#959;&#948;&#974;&#961;&#945;</foreign>, names that recur in Christian Sicilian funerary inscriptions (the former appears in an inscription from Catania of the Byzantine period, IMusCatania 191 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic003289">ISic003289</ref>, the latter in an inscription from Syracuse of the V-VI cent. CE, SEG 4.2 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic003178">ISic003178</ref>). The term <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#956;&#940;&#956;&#956;&#951;</foreign> (or <foreign xml:lang="grc">&#7936;&#956;&#956;&#942;</foreign>) is affective and recurs in another inscription from Catania of IV-V cent. CE, Libertini (1931), 44 no.7 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001629">ISic001629</ref>.</p>
            </div>
